But, that is necessary 'cause the technology has to always change to take into account advancements, same for computer software and hardware this is just a fact of space life. Utility in propulsion/power systems in space survives only when there is no competition for that particular 'Utility' system prompting a savings cost. <br>
The problem with nuclear space propulsion failure to fly so far is:<br>
1)nuke has not captured the public's imagination and interest, they know 'squat' only what the anti lobby has told them.<br>
2)nuke has not educated the public to its poignant need to access solar system and beyond to humans and robotics.<br>
3)nuke misconceptions over its use in space in the science community.<br>
4)lack of support for in-space fuel depot.<br>
5)lack of high altitude launch systems support structures.<br>
6)while launch prices have been lowered they are still to high to attract a space industry supply and demand.<br>
7)nuke space development in the government sector is subjected to a fickle politicos that give and take away funding as a result of which party is in power making continued space nuke R&amp;D difficult.<br>
<br>
Physics costs in propulsion: the more electrical power you employ the more mass you have to suffer with unless you can provide long time efficient quality thrust which is hard to do to haul big human packages; fine for light robotics.<br>
If you plan to haul humans around the solar system with all the trimmings people need to live in transit and keep ETA's short, you have to think &quot;big ass&quot; Nuclear Thermal Propulsion Systems with ass kick'in thrust for the short blast expelling  mass quantities of LH2,LOX in the near future...period!!  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :smileroll --><img src=http://www.smilies-world.de/Smilies/Smilies_klein_1/Smilies_klein_1_1/youpiaa.gif ALT=":smileroll"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=markix@nuclearspace>MarkIX</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Space Hotel Magnate</span><br>  Posts: 235<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(5/17/03 6:40 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=325.topic&index=25>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/3.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: How much cheaper are Nuclear rockets?</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>On &quot;space&quot; costs you're partly right...they're prototypes.<br>
