- is absolutely prohibited by international law, <br>
- has been publicly rejected by its creators,<br>
- has a microscopic band of supporters, (The cocept is not widely known and is controversial among those who are  aware. Not a good base to buld a gigantic space project from)<br>
- never had any testing even as a prototype,. Minature 3 foot, C4 powered putt-putts and plasma gunshots at mini pusherplates are not prototypes - they're don't even qualify as real proofs-of-concept.<br>
- Has serious unresolved potential show-stopping problems. A good percentage of the people who actually worked on the system believe that it has fatal problems. Does it? No one on Earth can claim that it doesn't. Major development and testing would be required to state with even minimal assurance, that the concept would function full-scale.<br>
- Even HERE, on a board which attracts hardcore nuclear space fanatics, has a majority opposed to ground launching an atomic bomb powered system - which is what your proposal is based upon. How do you think you will &quot;sell&quot; the idea of detonating 1,000s of atomic bombs in the biosphere when the majority of the public wishes to ban ANY nuclear detonations, even underground. Even John Fraz, a major Orion backer, has pointed out the need to avoid promoting atom bomb rockets when lobbying for nuclear propulsion support.<br>
<br>
Is Orion <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>technically</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> feasable? Maybe (or maybe not)<br>
Is Orion, used as you describe, capable of garnering the necessary support in the public? I cannot see that as a possibility. Consider that simply using RTGs, or creating small space reactors, results in fierce firestorms of controversy.<br>
Do you <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>REALISTICALLY</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> think that NASA's beleaguered chairman, in concert with the D.O.E. secretary (who is fighting a bloody battle to receive permission to upgrade <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>existing</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> nuclear weapons), joined by the Office of Management and Budget, will actually be convinced to propose such a plan as yours?<br>
<br>
